One of the most interesting programming 'hacks' is the Fast Inverse Square Root hack. Popularized by its use in the 3D computer game Quake III Arena.

```c++
float FastInvSqrt(float number) {
    long i;
    float x2, y;
    const float threehalfs = 1.5F;

    x2 = number * 0.5F;
    y  = number;
    i  = * ( long * ) &y; // evil floating point bit level hacking
    i  = 0x5f3759df - ( i >> 1 ); // what the fuck? 
    y  = * ( float * ) &i;
    y  = y * ( threehalfs - ( x2 * y * y ) ); // 1st iteration
    // y  = y * ( threehalfs - ( x2 * y * y ) ); // 2nd iteration, can be removed

    return y;
}
```

The hack is famous for its ability to calculate inverse square roots incredibly quickly (compared to the traditional method) but it also stands out due to the strange-looking number '0x5f3759df'. Despite looking like a magic number pulled out of thin air, this is actually a carefully selected approximation.

The reason it seems it shouldn't work is because it uses float-to-int reinterpretation. Let's break it down:
1) Bitwise operations on floating-point numbers does not make much sense, but this hack looks at the bit representation instead of treating it as a floating-point number.
2) The shift operation (i >> 1) effectively multiplies the exponent part of the float's bit representation by 0.5. This forms a very rough approximation of the square root.
3) The constant subtraction further refines this approximation.
4) Finally, Newton's method is applied to enhance the accuracy which usually gets pretty solid precision after one iteration.

Despite its seemingly magical operation, this hack is grounded in an understanding of the IEEE754 floating-point memory representation. It is not suitable in modern applications as hardware and compilers have improved making traditional methods faster and safer. Nevertheless, it remains a great example of coding ingenuity.

